{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6b4e8efd-7045-436a-9e6d-dd64f5a237a6","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** downloads the latest workload versions compatible with your current SDK. After an SDK update, this brings your workloads (like `maui`) in sync with the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** only *reinstalls* the already-installed versions. It fixes corrupted installs but won't pull in the newer workload packages that the updated SDK expects.\n\nSo the typical post-SDK-update fix is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, *then* try `dotnet workload repair` in case something got into a bad state during the update.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0f391b2-799f-49c1-87c4-fbe94f50cd6a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads. Use this when you've updated the SDK and need workloads to match.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted or incomplete installations. It does NOT update them to newer versions.\n\nAfter an SDK update, the right choice is `dotnet workload update`.","outputTokens":324},"id":"6dddea71-2ef6-4a52-8f9a-4d6035241ca6","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:42:53.490Z","parentId":"bbfd26a0-659f-4bd1-9d7a-00000b2db1dc"}
